Load libraries that I will use for exploring the data, and for cleaning it.

set.seed(2555)
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(data.table)

Read data for full Haute Born Wind farm from 2017 to 2020, and the data description file or metadata using the fread() function with data.table = FALSE:

haute_all_2017_2020 <- fread("la-haute-borne-data-2017-2020.csv", data.table = FALSE)
data_description <- fread("data_description.csv")

Make tibble of data:

haute <- tbl_df(haute_all_2017_2020)
metadata <- tbl_df(data_description)

Make a list of old names and one of replacement names from metadata:

old <- metadata[,"Variable_name"]
new <- metadata[, "Variable_long_name"]

Create a function to replace old names with a corresponding longer name on the new names list:

fast_clean <- function(df, x) {colnames(df) <- gsub (old[[c(1, x)]], new[[c(1, x)]], colnames(df)) ; df}

Apply the fast_clean function first to two column names that would create distortions in a while loop:

haute<- fast_clean(haute, 20)
haute<- fast_clean(haute, 27)

Use a while loop to take the old part of each column name and replace it by increments, skipping variable 20 and 27, which I have already done in the previous code chunk:

n <- 1
while(n < 20) {haute <- fast_clean(df = haute, x = n)
  n <- (n + 1)
  }
n <- 21
while(n < 27) {haute <- fast_clean(df = haute, x = n)
  n <- (n + 1)
  }
n <- 28
while(n <= 34) {haute <- fast_clean(df = haute, x = n)
  n <- (n + 1)
  }

Separate date and time in the datetime column:

haute <- separate(haute, "Date_time", c("date", "time"), sep = "T", remove = TRUE, convert = FALSE, extra = "warn", fill = "warn")

Make Date into date format:

haute$date <- as.Date(haute$date, "%Y-%m-%d")

The code is ready for some meaningful exploration. See “Exploratory Plots.rmd” .

What is the relationship between wind speed and active power?

From the plot below we can observe a strong positive relationship between Active Power and Wind Speed, and this makes intuitive sense.

ggplot(haute, aes(x = Wind_speed_avg, y = Active_power_avg))+
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Average Wind Speed (m/s)", y = "Active Power (kW)")

The same will be roughly true no matter which turbine we are looking at. Below, the data is faceted by individual turbine.

ggplot(haute, aes(x = Wind_speed_avg, y = Active_power_avg))+
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Average Wind Speed (m/s)", y = "Active Power (kW)") +
  facet_wrap(~Wind_turbine_name)

Can we learn anything more by mapping the date to color as seen below? The break away groupings in each of the turbines mostly seem to be in the chronologically earlier part of the sample, appearing as dark spikes to the left of the main grouping. Could it be that the turbines are running more efficiently sooner after installation? However, the highest points of efficiency (where there is wind speed around 5 m/s, and high active power) are later in the time series, lighter in color. Also, why might turbine R80711 have a significantly larger range of active power readings at the higher wind speeds? Above ~12.5 m/s, the correlation wind speed and active power becomes unclear. Its also interesting that there are these pools of datapoints along the bottom of each plot, where no matter how high

ggplot(haute, aes(x = Wind_speed_avg, y = Active_power_avg))+
  geom_point(aes(color = date, alpha = .5)) +
  labs(x = "Average Wind Speed (m/s)", y = "Active Power (kW)") +
  facet_wrap(~Wind_turbine_name)

Maybe we can limit our dates to the beginning of 2017 and figure out what might be going on. The plot below shows a more isolated cross section of the anomalous areas of the scatterplot above. For the two apparently deviating wind turbines (R80790 and R80711, upper left and lower right, respectively), the seeming spike in active power is roughly when the wind is between 3 and 6 m/s. More investigation would be necessary to determine how significant these clusters of data may be. Can we predict when this spike in efficiency will occur? Also visible here, in three out of four of the turbines in this period, there are many data points at which zero active power is recorded, and at wind speeds when we would expect to see Active Power increasing.

haute %>%
  filter(date < as.Date("2017-2-28")) %>%
  filter(Wind_speed_avg < 7) %>%
  filter(Wind_speed_avg > 2) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x = Wind_speed_avg, y = Active_power_avg))+
  labs(x = "Average Wind Speed (m/s)", y = "Active Power (kW)") +
  geom_point(aes(color = date), alpha = .5) +
  facet_wrap(~Wind_turbine_name) +
  geom_smooth()

Now lets try comparing wind speeds over time, and how the active power is affected. Maybe that will clarify some things. Over a full year period, the plot below shows some densely packed periods of wind increase and decrease, with a generally corresponding increase and decrease of Active Power. The dark spikes seem to indicate low to zero active power at high wind speeds.

ggplot(haute, aes(x = date, y = Wind_speed_avg)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Active_power_avg))+
  geom_smooth() +
  labs(x = "Date", y = "Average Wind Speed (m/s)") +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "6 month") +
  facet_wrap(~Wind_turbine_name)

As an experiment, lets try to isolate the darkest spike in the R80790 time series. Since this is an unexpected lack of Active Power at high wind speeds, we’ll filter out that turbine, and filter a date range that will give us a better spread of data points in our plot, a nine day period in which the spike occurs. We’ll continue mapping Active Power to color, but change the date break to 1 day instead of 6 months so we can see which days exactly we are talking about. The plot, shown below, tells us that the spike from the plot above is really just a two day period, February 3rd and 4th of 2017, when despite the windy conditions, and the three other turbines producing power, this turbine was not producing. We might be able to figure out if it was down for service from looking at service records, or we can read into the data to figure out if something else was created a fault and if there might be a way to predicet that fault, if in fact it can be considered a fault.

haute %>%
  filter(date < as.Date("2017-02-8")) %>%
  filter(date > as.Date("2017-01-29")) %>%
  filter(Wind_turbine_name == "R80790") %>%

In all 4 wind turbines there is a cluster offshoot where the relationship between active power and reactive power is inverted. This is interesting but may be beyond the scope of this project, and beyond my domain knowledge. I will stick with the relationship between wind speed and active power. In particular I am interested in those data points where Wind Speed is high enough that we would expect a certain level of Active Power, but in fact the Active Power is below a certain threshold. I will define this more specifically in the feature engineering phase of the project.

Feature Engineering

In the exploration phase of the project, there was a lot that jumped out as interesting. But I decided to focus on instances of turbines not functioning as intended. This will require first some feature engineering. I will create a new feature “down” that displays a 1 if the wind speed is above 5 m/s but average active power is below 50 kW. In other words, a feature that tells me when a turbine “should” be producing power, but is not. This is a simplification, but it sets us up with a binary feature that could be re-engineered in many different ways, and one that allows for the application of machine learning approaches like logistic regression and k-fold Cross Validation.

down <- ifelse(haute$Wind_speed_avg > 5 & haute$Active_power_avg < 50, 1, 0)
summary(down)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##  0.0000  0.0000  0.0000  0.0115  0.0000  1.0000    1658
haute$down <- as.factor(down)
class(haute$down)
## [1] "factor"

Here I want to create a subset that includes all of my features, including min and max values, and the new feature down but remove turbine ID, date, time. Since I wont be doing any time series analysis. I will also remove all wind and power related features, since they are baked into the feature “down”.

down <- haute$down
haute_clean <- select(haute, -c(1,2,3))
haute_clean <- haute_clean %>%
                  select(-contains("Wind")) %>%
                  select(-contains("Power"))

Here I see that some columns have almost as many missing values as there are rows, but I will not worry about that for now. A bigger concern is that the feature “down” has a number of missing values. I will remove the 1658 rows in which down is NA using the drop_na function from tidyr:

haute_complete <- haute_clean %>%
                drop_na(down)

I will remove the columns from the dataset with the most NAs (where over a third of rows are missing values). This could be a place for further experimentation later on, but for now, I will remove them.

haute_complete <- haute_clean
haute_complete <- haute_complete %>%
                  select(-contains("Vane_position")) %>%
                  select(-contains("Nacelle_angle_corrected"))

Machine Learning

The positive cases of “down” is only about 1.2%. Which means I will need to balance the data to create a logistic regression model. I will use the SMOTE function from the caret package which combines upsampling and downsampling. This produces a dataset with about 17,000 observations, and a balance of 75/25.

library(caret)
library(DMwR)
set.seed(2555)
smote_haute <- SMOTE(down ~ ., data = as.data.frame(haute_complete))
smoted_haute <- table(smote_haute$down)
smoted_haute
## 
##    0    1 
## 9846 7437
smoted_haute[2]/smoted_haute[1]
##         1 
## 0.7553321
smote_haute <- tbl_df(smote_haute)

Now I want to check out the missing values after using SMOTE:

Now I want to create a logistic regression model with the clean and balanced dataset, in which there are no missing values for “down”. Additionally, and this is absolutely key to getting a result: I must use na.omit on the dataset before splitting it. I will split the balanced data into a train and test set with split.seed from caTools.

library(caTools)
smote_haute_omitted <- na.omit(smote_haute)               
split <- sample.split(smote_haute_omitted$down, SplitRatio = .65)
train <- subset(smote_haute_omitted, split == TRUE)
test <- subset(smote_haute_omitted, split == FALSE)
table(train$down)
## 
##    0    1 
## 6304 3914
table(test$down)
## 
##    0    1 
## 3394 2107

I will create a logistic regression model to predict down, based on the training data.

trainlogistic <- glm(down ~ ., data = train, family = binomial)

Predictions

Now I will predict in the test set which turbines are down, using the logistic regression model I have just made

predictTest <- predict(trainlogistic, type = "response", newdata = test)
table(test$down)
## 
##    0    1 
## 3394 2107
table(test$down, predictTest > .5)
##    
##     FALSE TRUE
##   0  3270  124
##   1    34 2073

I will visualize the results in a confusion matrix:

input.matrix <- data.matrix(table(test$down, predictTest > .5))

colnames(input.matrix) = c(FALSE, TRUE)
rownames(input.matrix) = c(0, 1)

glmconfusion <- as.data.frame(as.table(input.matrix))
b <- c(0, 1800, 3500)
plot <- ggplot(glmconfusion)
plot + 
  geom_tile(aes(x=Var1, y=Var2, fill=Freq)) +
        labs(fill = "Normalized\nFrequency") +
        scale_x_discrete(name="Actual Class") + 
        scale_y_discrete(name="Predicted Class") + 
        scale_fill_gradient(breaks=b, labels = format(b)) + 
        ggtitle("Logistic Regression: Predicted vs. Actual")

I will measure the performance of this model overall by measuring the area under the ROC curve and plotting it.

library(ROCR)
ROCRpred <- prediction(predictTest, test$down)
as.numeric(performance(ROCRpred, "auc")@y.values)
## [1] 0.993741
perf <- performance(ROCRpred,"tpr","fpr")
plot(perf,colorize=TRUE)

The area under an ROC curve is .9913. As a measure of accuracy for this model, which is more accurate than the baseline of .9885. But all the same, could be used to predict down turbines with an accceptable degree of accuracy in the event that no wind or power data is available.

Logistic regression produces some result, though it is problematic (I will talk about this in the report). I will try cross validation.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, savePredictions = TRUE)

mod_fit <- train(down ~ .,  data = train, method="glm", family="binomial",
                 trControl = ctrl, tuneLength = 5)

predCV <- predict(mod_fit, newdata = test)

summary(predCV)
##    0    1 
## 3304 2197

And visualize the confusion matrix for this as well.

table(predCV, test$down)
##       
## predCV    0    1
##      0 3270   34
##      1  124 2073
confusion2 <- confusionMatrix(data = predCV, test$down)

input.matrix2 <- data.matrix(table(test$down, predictTest > .5))


colnames(input.matrix2) = c(FALSE, TRUE)
rownames(input.matrix2) = c(0, 1)

confusion2 <- as.data.frame(as.table(input.matrix))
b <- c(0, 1800, 3500)
plot2 <- ggplot(confusion2)
plot2 + 
  geom_tile(aes(x=Var1, y=Var2, fill=Freq)) +
        labs(fill = "Normalized\nFrequency") +
        scale_x_discrete(name="Actual Class") + 
        scale_y_discrete(name="Predicted Class") + 
        scale_fill_gradient(breaks=b, labels = format(b)) + 
        ggtitle("10-Fold Cross Validation: Predicted vs. Actual")
